post_text:
In accordance with New Jersey guidance, Merchantville School will require students to wear masks throughout the school day. Parents should consider purchasing a mask that children can become comfortable with in the coming weeks before school.
For parents worried their kids won’t be able to wear masks for long periods of time this Fall, try this rule for your last few weeks of summer: You’re only allowed screen time if you’re wearing a mask. Either they will acclimate quickly, or you’ll get them off devices for the last weeks of their summer.

post_text:
Merchantville School has a re-opening committee including representatives from the administration, board of education, teachers, nurses, parents, police and borough council. A survey will be sent out later this week to poll the community on re-opening school in September. The goal is to have a plan in place at the end of July that follows the state guidelines and ensures the best solutions for our students.

Please know that parents set the tone for children. When the plans are announced, read them in private and discuss with other adults in your house. Then come back and tell your children as cheerfully as possible how the Fall will go. Buy or make them a mask that they pick out and tell them how proud you are of them for wanting to keep others safe. Tell them to try their best. They are watching your reaction and will respond accordingly. Even if you are frustrated or upset, the best advice is to be a positive as possible with your child about the upcoming school year. Children do not need to add your worries to their own.

post_text:
Dear Camp Invention and Invention Project parents,

Recently, you should have received an email regarding us having to cancel camp this summer. Camp Invention and Invention Project are offering different options with camp packages that you can refer to if you are interested in some fun hands on STEM activities at home. If you'd like to discuss refund options, call in to speak with a representative so they can verify where to return the funds to and get everything processed. Please call in at 800-968-4332. Due to call volume, there might be a 5-15 minute wait, but the best thing for you to do is just wait on the line because a rep will certainly be able to help you out once they get through. Voicemails and call-backs are okay, but again the easiest way to get through is just to wait. Right now they are super busy with calls to modify camp and customer needs. If you have any other questions or concerns, please feel free to reach out to Adrienne Browne at browne@merchantville.k12.nj.us . We thank you for your continued patience and support and wish everyone a safe & healthy summer.

post_text: The Merchantville Education Association would like to invite students, parents and the community to Merchantville School’s end of year drive-by parade. This parade is to honor and celebrate three of our fabulous teachers (Mrs. Fields, Mrs. Batterman and Mrs. Gandy) who are retiring this year and to give them the proper sendoff they deserve! The parade is also an opportunity for students and staff to wave good-bye before summer vacation begins. The parade will take place on Friday, June 12th from 2-3pm. Once in the lot, cars will be directed through the staff parking lot and then turn right to drive down Centre Street. Retiring teachers will be set up in the staff parking lot if anyone would like to drop off or send well wishes. Teachers and staff will be standing on the sidewalk along Centre Street. To continue with social distancing, please remain in your cars during the parade and wave to your teachers from a safe distance. We hope to see you there!

We hope you are staying safe and healthy during these unprecedented times. Although we are facing a crisis like never before, it is amazing to see the acts of generosity, support, and resilience happening throughout our communities. It is especially heartening to see how uKNIGHTed our Merchantville School community has been throughout the past month. The love and support felt during our school parade last week inspired our Merchantville School Student Council members to organize a fundraiser. We are hosting a fundraiser with a sale of "uKNIGHTed" apparel to show that we are a strong and unified community. All proceeds will be donated to various efforts throughout our community to aid Covid-19 relief.

The link to the online store can be found by clicking below. Our fundraiser will end on 5/5.

post_text:
We are currently a part of living history. Our children are a part of this quarantine and will talk about this for years to come. Schools are closed, sports are canceled and people are quarantined - around the world.
One of the best things that you can do with your children is keep a journal over the next weeks. Have children find a method to document this historic event in pictures, videos, drawings, word or any medium. Have them reach out to others and document the feelings and views of everyone during this time. This promotes story telling skills in a variety of formats.
Preserve their work and save it because they will want to come back to it and share it with others. Help them create a tangible source of their account of this quarantine.

post_text: Merchantville School students learned about "Día de los Muertos", a Mexican holiday where people celebrate the lives of loved ones who have passed away. While celebrated throughout Mexico, it is also recognized in Central and South America, Europe and Asia, as well as in parts of the United States. This special celebration takes place November 1st and 2nd. Students learned about the importance of the tradition and popular symbols of Día de los Muertos.

post_text:
Merchantville School stresses the importance of reading to the students. This week is designated "Read Across Our Community" where our students will participate in a variety of activities to promote reading.
Today classes welcomed guest readers and classes took trips to various locations in Merchantville to hear from guest readers. Thank you to all the people that took time to promote the most important life long skill that students need in order to succeed - READING.
It was a great success and all involved had a great time.

post_text: Take fun to the next level with Invention Project®, a one-of-a-kind program for students entering grades 6-9. Invention Project empowers each student to be an innovator by bringing new ideas to life while tackling real-world topics. Merchantville School is hosting Invention Project from August 5th to August 9th. Check out invent.org/invention-project or call 800-968-4332 for registration information! Look for Flyers coming home this week!

post_text: Merchantville School celebrated Black History month with an assembly focusing on American Civil Rights through movement and audience participation. Students heard the words of Dr. King and learned how non-violent actions helped end segregation. Classes then completed an activity to follow up with the assembly. Quotes from famous African-Americans were highlighted on the morning announcements. Our TVs displayed information about influential people in the African-American community. We continued to promote our "No Place for Hate" initiative where all students are accepted for who they are.

post_text:
In many ways, 1st grade is a year of important transitions — children leave behind much of the play of preschool and kindergarten and dive into developing deeper academic skills. First graders progress from having beginner reading and writing skills to becoming beginning readers and writers, as they not only read and write more often, but with greater comprehension and ability, too.
Merchantville School provides a wonderful and fun environment for our first grade students to learn and have fun every day.
